[2026-05-02 09:41:26.35972] [526998] [debug] 	<pre>
[2026-05-02 09:41:26.35974] [526998] [debug] 	Note: GraphViz2::DBI ships with db.schema.pl, which creates an SVG image of a schema
[2026-05-02 09:41:26.35975] [526998] [debug] 	- To run it you need to set three environment variables as below
[2026-05-02 09:41:26.35976] [526998] [debug] 	- dbi.schema.pl takes an option parameter of image type, which defaults to svg
[2026-05-02 09:41:26.35978] [526998] [debug] 	- Edit the code if you wish to change the output dir's name
[2026-05-02 09:41:26.35979] [526998] [debug] 	- The last line, the copy, is for my setup. $DR points to a RAM disk. Debian automatically creates a RAM disk, so I configure the free web server Engine X, aka nginx, to use it. See my other TiddlyWiki, Debian.Wiki.html, for details about nginx
[2026-05-02 09:41:26.35981] [526998] [debug] 	- And yes, you can use empty strings for the username and password
[2026-05-02 09:41:26.35982] [526998] [debug] 	- Lastly, $ is just the command line prompt
[2026-05-02 09:41:26.35984] [526998] [debug] 	$ DBI_DSN=dbi:SQLite:dbname=data/levies.sqlite
[2026-05-02 09:41:26.35985] [526998] [debug] 	$ DBI_USER=local
[2026-05-02 09:41:26.35986] [526998] [debug] 	$ DBI_PASS=local
[2026-05-02 09:41:26.35988] [526998] [debug] 	$ export DBI_DSN DBI_USER DBI_PASS
[2026-05-02 09:41:26.35989] [526998] [debug] 	$ mkdir html
[2026-05-02 09:41:26.35991] [526998] [debug] 	$ dbi.schema.pl (my version)
[2026-05-02 09:41:26.35992] [526998] [debug] 	$ cp html/dbi.schema.svg $DR/levy.schema.svg
[2026-05-02 09:41:26.35994] [526998] [debug] 	</pre>
